## Part 1 — Who He Is

### The Writer

E.I. Werner is Evan Werner, 33. He decided at 15 he would be a fantasy author. Not wanted to be — decided. That decision has organized nearly everything since: eighteen years of writing almost every day, a string of career moves designed to fund the art, and a project of genuinely unusual ambition that is still in progress and still getting bigger.

The eighteen years matter more than any single credential. He has a published tabletop game credit — quests he wrote for Kinfire Chronicles, a Kickstarted game that shipped to acclaim, with characters he created surviving multiple expansions. He landed a literary agent for a completed fantasy novel that went out to every major publisher on earth. He co-wrote a feature screenplay about the first marathon runner in ancient Athens that is currently out to directors through a WME-connected manager. He is not a hobbyist. He is a working writer who has not yet published a book.

That gap — eighteen years of real, serious work, and almost nothing to show for it in the way the world measures — is the engine of everything. It is the brand. Not as tragedy. As proof.

### The Project — ONCE and Only Us

His primary writing project is ONCE: six original creation myths forming the complete cosmology of a fantasy world. These are not worldbuilding notes. He has built a moral philosophy from scratch — answers to the questions every civilization must answer: What are we for? What is evil? What happens when we die? What do we owe each other? — and followed each answer to its consequences, including the ugly ones. Gender, death, value, labor, sex, slavery, suicide, ecology, governance. Every piece flows from the cosmology. It is load-bearing all the way down.

He has been developing these myths for over two years. He is finishing them this year in a year-long writing workshop called Analog, led by Ravi Gupta, host of the Lost Debate podcast and author of Garbage Town. He joined the class for free after reconnecting with Ravi in Costa Rica.

The myths are the foundation for Only Us, a fantasy trilogy that reimagines Joseph from Genesis as a king's daughter who ascends despite betrayal. When the myths are done, the novel follows. He has decided — correctly — to finish the foundation before building on top of it, rather than trying to plan the novel while the cosmology is still open.

His differentiator as a creator is not that he reviews and ranks other people's fantasy. It is that he is actually building something. The ONCE myths are his primary shareable content until the novel exists — not teaser material, but the thing itself.

### What He Believes

> *"Writing, fantasy, and games are not escapes. They are destinations."*

This is not a slogan. It is a position that contradicts the mainstream framing of his entire genre, and he can defend it from the mythology up. Fantasy is not where you go to avoid the world. It is one of the few places where certain truths can be stated directly — truths that realism can only approximate. The greatest fantasy has always known this. He is building toward it.

He believes pure passion, held without apology for long enough, becomes proof of something. Not naivety. Not delusion. Evidence. Eighteen years of the same thing, with almost nothing to show for it, and he is still going. That is the signal. That is what the brand carries.

